docs.abstract: Readers around the world tell us about the global ripple effect of the U.S. election.
docs.snippet: Readers around the world tell us about the global ripple effect of the U.S. election.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Mr. Biden has vowed to turn the page on the ‘aberration’ of Mr. Trump’s foreign policy,” wrote Robert Malley and Philip H. Gordon in the Op-Ed “Trump Still Has 70 Days to Wreak Havoc Around the World.” But is that what people around the world really want?

headline.main: ‘Democracy Should Not Be Taken for Granted’

byline.original: By Rachel L. Harris and Lisa Tarchak

docs.abstract: President Trump told suburban voters that affordable housing would hurt property values and increase crime. The story of one Wisconsin community challenges those assumptions.
docs.snippet: President Trump told suburban voters that affordable housing would hurt property values and increase crime. The story of one Wisconsin community challenges those assumptions.
docs.lead_paragraph: NEW BERLIN, Wis. — When John Blaguski first heard about a proposal to build an affordable housing complex near his home in the Milwaukee suburb of New Berlin, Wis., his mind drifted to stereotypes of crime-ridden, shoddily constructed projects.

headline.main: Residents Feared Low-Income Housing Would Ruin Their Suburb. It Didn’t.

docs.abstract: DETROIT — Holly Lambert, part of a thinning crowd in front of the TCF Center in Detroit, has been anxiously awaiting the outcome of the presidential election. She said on Friday that she believed her freedoms were at stake if Joseph R. Biden Jr. were declared the winner.

headline.main: ‘I stay up all night waiting and praying,’ says one protester in Detroit.

docs.abstract: Democrats agree that Ms. Abrams’s political vision helped deliver Georgia to Joe Biden. In an interview with The New York Times, she lays out why 2020 was the year it came together.
docs.snippet: Democrats agree that Ms. Abrams’s political vision helped deliver Georgia to Joe Biden. In an interview with The New York Times, she lays out why 2020 was the year it came together.
docs.lead_paragraph: After years of close calls, red herrings, and electoral margins that grew closer and closer, Democrats won Georgia in this year’s presidential election for the first time since 1992.

headline.main: Why Stacey Abrams Is Confident Georgia Will Stay Blue
headline.print_headline: Abrams Helped Turn Georgia Blue. She Thinks It Can Stay That Way.

docs.abstract: Joseph R. Biden Jr. campaigned as a sober and conventional presence, concerned about the “soul of the country.” He correctly judged the character of the country, and benefited from President Trump’s missteps.
docs.snippet: Joseph R. Biden Jr. campaigned as a sober and conventional presence, concerned about the “soul of the country.” He correctly judged the character of the country, and benefited from President Trump’s missteps.
docs.lead_paragraph: On a January evening in 2019, Joseph R. Biden Jr. placed a call to the mayor of Los Angeles, Eric Garcetti, a personal friend and political ally who had just announced he would not pursue the Democratic nomination for president.

headline.main: How Joe Biden Won the Presidency
headline.print_headline: Focus on Character Spurred Winner’s Successful Bid

byline.original: By Alexander Burns, Jonathan Martin and Katie Glueck

docs.abstract: As the nation awaits results in what has turned out to be a historic election in a historic year, we look back to the elections after the Voting Rights Act.
docs.snippet: As the nation awaits results in what has turned out to be a historic election in a historic year, we look back to the elections after the Voting Rights Act.
docs.lead_paragraph: Today marks the conclusion of a fraught political season like no other, with the denouement coming amid deep divisions over the future of the country and a coronavirus pandemic that has claimed more than 230,000 American lives. It also has come in the wake of a number of police killings, which sparked tremendous unrest and demonstrations against systemic racism and police brutality.

headline.main: Photos From The 1960s: Black Americans Voting For the First Time

docs.abstract: With Parliament considering a security bill, officers used tear gas and dispersal grenades in their response to a camp set up in a prominent square to protest against a lack of housing.
docs.snippet: With Parliament considering a security bill, officers used tear gas and dispersal grenades in their response to a camp set up in a prominent square to protest against a lack of housing.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — The police cleared out a temporary migrant camp in central Paris, forcing people out of tents, chasing them in the streets and firing tear gas in a crackdown that fueled growing outrage over the government’s tough new security policies.

headline.main: Outcry in France After Police Clear Paris Migrant Camp
headline.print_headline: ‘I Was Stunned’: Outcry as Paris Police Dispel Migrant Camp

docs.abstract: Young people staged the biggest anti-government uprising in a generation, triggered by relentless police brutality. Rattled, politicians are promising reforms, but using repressive tactics, large and small.
docs.snippet: Young people staged the biggest anti-government uprising in a generation, triggered by relentless police brutality. Rattled, politicians are promising reforms, but using repressive tactics, large and small.
docs.lead_paragraph: LAGOS, Nigeria — Nigeria’s leaders have made a show of responding to the demands of a massive youth-led uprising over police brutality that recently brought the country to a standstill and captured global attention.

headline.main: Nigeria Goes on Offensive Against Youth Protesting Police Brutality
headline.print_headline: Nigeria Goes on Offensive Against Youth Protesting Police Brutality

docs.abstract: The coronavirus pandemic has put a dent in the signature-gathering process, but voters still managed to put forward dozens of measures nationwide.
docs.snippet: The coronavirus pandemic has put a dent in the signature-gathering process, but voters still managed to put forward dozens of measures nationwide.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — If ever there was a doubt about the coronavirus’s impact on American democracy, look no further than the sharp decline in citizen initiatives this year. There are 38 such measures slated across the country, around half the level in the last presidential election, when there were 72.

headline.main: Taxes, Heroin and Statehood: A Glimpse Into This Year’s Ballot Measures
headline.print_headline: Ballot Measures Decline, But Aren’t to Be Ignored

docs.abstract: I learned how to carry myself to protect my safety back home, only to come to the U.S. and face a different danger.
docs.snippet: I learned how to carry myself to protect my safety back home, only to come to the U.S. and face a different danger.
docs.lead_paragraph: I came to the United States in 2019 as a scholar-at-risk fellow at Harvard University. After I was kidnapped and tortured in Nigeria for being gay and daring to speak openly about it America offered me refuge. But this spring after videos of the killings of Ahmaud Arbery and George Floyd surfaced, I’m coming to terms with the fact that the country that promised me safety is one where Black men like me face a different kind of danger.

headline.main: Gay in Nigeria, Black Male in America
